definition.value: A macrolide lactam containing a 23-membered lactone ring, originally isolated from the fermentation broth of a Japanese soil sample that contained the bacteria Streptomyces tsukubaensis.
Any lipid carrying one or more hydroperoxy substituents.
A hydrate that is the monohydrate form of tacrolimus.
An inorganic radical in which a free electron resides on one or more oxygen atoms of an oxygen species.
A nucleoside bisphosphate that has a purine nucleobase.
A nucleoside bisphosphate where sugar of the nucleoside is ribose.
A nucleotide-sugar whose nucleobase is a pyrimidine.
An EC 3.5.1.* (non-peptide linear amide C-N hydrolase) inhibitor that interferes with the function of histone deacetylase (EC 3.5.1.98).
Any compound that has a nucleobase as a part.
Any member of the group of bioactive lipids made by oxidation of polyunsaturated fatty acids.
An octadecadienoic acid having a system of two conjugated double bonds at any position.
A  nucleotide having adenine as the base.
A purine riboncleotide where adenine is the purine.
A glycerate in which at least one of the hydroxy groups has been phosphorylated.

A steroid that has a structure based on a 21-carbon (pregnane) skeleton. Note that individual examples may have ring substituents at other positions and/or contain double bonds, aromatic A-rings, expanded/contracted rings etc., so the formula and mass may vary from that given for the generic structure.
A C20, straight-chain, polyunsaturated fatty acid anion containing five double bonds.
A dicarboxylate that contains four carbon atoms.
Any hydroxy carboxylic acid which contains a hydroxy group located beta- to the carboxylic acid group.
A compound containing a sulfonic acid residue joined by a carbon-sulfur bond to a lipid.
A polymer, composed of polyanion macromolecules.
An amino acid zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of N(2)-acetyl-L-lysine; major species at pH 7.3.
An organophosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of D-fructofuranose 6-phosphate; major species at pH 7.3.
An organophosphate oxoanion resulting from deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of D-glucopyranose 6-phosphate; major species at pH 7.3.
The five-membered ring form of D-fructose 6-phosphate.
A ribonucleoside triphosphate oxoanion arising from global deprotonation of the  triphosphate groups of any nucleoside triphosphate; major species at pH 7.3.
The organophosphate oxoanion formed from D-hexopyranose 6-phosphate by loss of two protons from the phosphate group; principal species at pH 7.3.
Any saponin derived from a hydroxysteroid.
Any D-hexose 6-phosphate in which the hexose is in the pyranose form.
A dipeptide consisting of glycine having an L-prolyl group attached to its alpha-amino nitrogen.
The zwitterion of L-prolinylglycine resulting from the transfer of a proton from the hydroxy group of glycine to the amino group of proline. Major microspecies at pH 7.3.
Any organic molecular entity derived from a fatty acid.
A fatty acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of any short-chain fatty acid.

An EC 1.14.13.* (oxidoreductase acting on paired donors, incorporating 1 atom of oxygen, with NADH or NADPH as one donor) inhibitor that interferes with the action of nitric oxide synthase (EC 1.14.13.39).
A fatty acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of any branched-chain fatty acid.
Any substance that interacts with tubulin to promote polymerisation of microtubules.
Any substance that interacts with tubulin to inhibit polymerisation of microtubules.
An alpha-amino-acid residue derived from trans-4-hydroxy-L-proline.
An alpha-amino-acid residue derived from O(4)-phospho-L-tyrosine.
An alpha-amino-acid residue anion derived from O(4)-phosphonato-L-tyrosine(2-)
Zwitterionic form of a polar amino acid having an anionic carboxy group and a protonated amino group.
Any donor that can transfer acyl groups between molecular entities.
An alkanesulfonate in which the carbon at position 1 is attached to at least two hydrogens.
An organosulfonate oxoanion resulting from the removal of a proton from the sulfonic acid group of metamizole.

A pyrazole that is antiipyrine substituted at C-4 by a methyl(sulfomethyl)amino group, the sodium salt of which, metamizole sodium, was widely used as a powerful analgesic and antipyretic, but withdrawn from many markets from the 1970s due to a risk of causing risk of causing agranulocytosis.
An  EC 1.4.* (oxidoreductase acting on donor CH-NH2 group) inhibitor that interferes with the action of any glutamate synthase.
A class of secondary metabolites developed by many plants to influence the behaviour, growth or survival of herbivores, and thus acting as a defence against herbivory.
An optically active form of O(4)-phosphonatotyrosine(2-) having L-configuration.
A monocarboxylic acid anion resulting from the deprotonation of the carboxyl group of indole-3-carboxylic acid.

A molecular messenger in which the molecule is specifically involved in transmitting information between cells. Such molecules are released from the cell sending the signal, cross over the gap between cells by diffusion, and interact with specific receptors in another cell, triggering a response in that cell by activating a series of enzyme controlled reactions which lead to changes inside the cell.
A quaternary ammonium ion that is the conjugate acid of sphingomyelin d18:1, obtined by protonation of the anionic phosphate function.
